<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Vocabulary">Vocabulary</h2>=
</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numeral_(linguistics)#Fr=
actional_numbers" title=3D"Numeral (linguistics)">Numeral (linguistics) =C2=
=A7&nbsp;Fractional numbers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
nglish_numerals#Fractions_and_decimals" title=3D"English numerals">English =
numerals =C2=A7&nbsp;Fractions and decimals</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicode_subscripts_and_superscripts#Fraction_slash" titl=
e=3D"Unicode subscripts and superscripts">Unicode subscripts and superscrip=
ts =C2=A7&nbsp;Fraction slash</a></div>
<p>In a fraction, the number of equal parts being described is the <b>numer=
ator</b> (from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Latin language">Latin</a>: <i lang=3D"la">numer=
=C4=81tor</i>, "counter" or "numberer"), and the type or variety of the par=
ts is the <b>denominator</b> (from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Latin_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Latin language">Latin</a>: =
<i lang=3D"la">d=C4=93n=C5=8Dmin=C4=81tor</i>, "thing that names or designa=
tes").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-schwartzman_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-schwartzman-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As an example, the fraction <link =
rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r121440=
2035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"nu=
m">8</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">5</span></sp=
an>=E2=81=A0</span> amounts to eight parts, each of which is of the type na=
med <i>fifth</i>. In terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divi=
sion_(math)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Division (math)">division</a>, =
the numerator corresponds to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
ivision_(math)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Division (math)">dividend</a=
>, and the denominator corresponds to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Division_(math)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Division (math)">di=
visor</a>.
</p><p>Informally, the numerator and denominator may be distinguished by pl=
acement alone, but in formal contexts they are usually separated by a <b>fr=
action bar</b>. The fraction bar may be horizontal (as in <link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span=
 class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=
<span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">3</span></span>=E2=81=
=A0</span>), oblique (as in 2/5), or diagonal (as in <link rel=3D"mw-dedupl=
icated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span clas=
s=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">4</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">9</span=
></span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ambrose_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-ambrose-5"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These=
 marks are respectively known as the horizontal bar; the virgule, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slash_mark" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Slash mark">slash</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/America=
n_English" title=3D"American English">US</a>), or <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Oblique_stroke" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Oblique stro=
ke">stroke</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_English" t=
itle=3D"British English">UK</a>); and the fraction bar, solidus,<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fr=
action#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Fraction_slash" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fraction slash">fraction sla=
sh</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>n 2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typography" title=3D"Typography">typography</a>, frac=
tions stacked vertically are also known as <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/En_(typography)" title=3D"En (typography)">en</a></i> or <i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/En_dash" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"En dash">nut</a> fractions</i>, and diagonal ones as <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Em_(typography)" title=3D"Em (typography)">em</a>=
</i> or <i>mutton fractions</i>, based on whether a fraction with a single-=
digit numerator and denominator occupies the proportion of a narrow <i>en</=
i> square, or a wider <i>em</i> square.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ambrose_5-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_not=
e-ambrose-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> In traditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Typefounding" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Typefounding">typefoundin=
g</a>, a piece of type bearing a complete fraction (e.g. <link rel=3D"mw-de=
duplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span =
class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><=
span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0=
</span>) was known as a <i>case fraction</i>, while those representing only=
 parts of fractions were called <i>piece fractions</i>.
</p><p>The denominators of English fractions are generally expressed as <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinal_number_(linguistics)#Variatio=
ns" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ordinal number (linguistics)">ordinal nu=
mbers</a>, in the plural if the numerator is not 1. (For example, <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r121440203=
5"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">=
2</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">5</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span> and <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-=
data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">3</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span=
 class=3D"den">5</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> are both read as a number of=
 <i>fifths</i>.) Exceptions include the denominator 2, which is always read=
 <i>half</i> or <i>halves</i>, the denominator 4, which may be alternativel=
y expressed as <i>quarter</i>/<i>quarters</i> or as <i>fourth</i>/<i>fourth=
s</i>, and the denominator 100, which may be alternatively expressed as <i>=
hundredth</i>/<i>hundredths</i> or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Percent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Percent">percent</a></i>.
</p><p>When the denominator is 1, it may be expressed in terms of <i>wholes=
</i> but is more commonly ignored, with the numerator read out as a whole n=
umber. For example, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-d=
ata:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">3</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span=
 class=3D"den">1</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> may be described as <i>three=
 wholes</i>, or simply as <i>three</i>. When the numerator is 1, it may be =
omitted (as in <i>a tenth</i> or <i>each quarter</i>).
</p><p>The entire fraction may be expressed as a single composition, in whi=
ch case it is hyphenated, or as a number of fractions with a numerator of o=
ne, in which case they are not. (For example, <i>two-fifths</i> is the frac=
tion <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSty=
les:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span =
class=3D"num">2</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">5=
</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> and <i>two fifths</i> is the same fraction u=
nderstood as 2 instances of <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<spa=
n class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</spa=
n><span class=3D"den">5</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>.) Fractions should al=
ways be hyphenated when used as adjectives. Alternatively, a fraction may b=
e described by reading it out as the numerator <i>over</i> the denominator,=
 with the denominator expressed as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Cardinal_number" title=3D"Cardinal number">cardinal number</a>. (For exa=
mple, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSt=
yles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span=
 class=3D"num">3</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">=
1</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> may also be expressed as <i>three over one<=
/i>.) The term <i>over</i> is used even in the case of solidus fractions, w=
here the numbers are placed left and right of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Slash_mark" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Slash mark">slash =
mark</a>. (For example, 1/2 may be read <i>one-half</i>, <i>one half</i>, o=
r <i>one over two</i>.) Fractions with large denominators that are <i>not</=
i> powers of ten are often rendered in this fashion (e.g., <link rel=3D"mw-=
deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><spa=
n class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span=
><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">117</span></span>=E2=
=81=A0</span> as <i>one over one hundred seventeen</i>), while those with d=
enominators divisible by ten are typically read in the normal ordinal fashi=
on (e.g., <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templa=
teStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><=
span class=3D"num">6</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"d=
en">1000000</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> as <i>six-millionths</i>, <i>six =
millionths</i>, or <i>six one-millionths</i>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Forms_of_fractions">Forms o=
f fractions</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Simple,_common,_or_vulgar_f=
ractions"><span id=3D"Simple.2C_common.2C_or_vulgar_fractions"></span>Simpl=
e, common, or vulgar fractions<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Simple_fraction"=
></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Common_fraction"></span><span class=3D=
"anchor" id=3D"Vulgar_fraction"></span></h3></div>
<p>A <b>simple fraction</b> (also known as a <b>common fraction</b> or <b>v=
ulgar fraction</b>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vulgar_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-vulgar-1"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>n 1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D=
"Rational number">rational number</a> written as <i>a</i>/<i>b</i> or <span=
 class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element=
