h <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integers" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Integers">integers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-11"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 As with other fractions, the denominator (<i>b</i>) cannot be zero. Exampl=
es include <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templ=
ateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion">=
<span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"=
den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, =E2=88=92<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated=
-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"s=
frac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">8</span><span class=
=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">5</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, <=
link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1=
214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=
=3D"num">=E2=88=928</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"de=
n">5</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, and <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline=
-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=
=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">8</span><span class=3D"sr=
-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">=E2=88=925</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>=
. The term was originally used to distinguish this type of fraction from th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexagesimal#Fractions" title=3D"=
Sexagesimal">sexagesimal fraction</a> used in astronomy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Smith1958_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fraction#cite_note-Smith1958-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Common fractions can be positive or negative, and they can be <i>pro=
per</i> or <i>improper</i> (see below). Compound fractions, complex fractio=
ns, mixed numerals, and decimal expressions (see below) are not <i>common f=
ractions</i>; though, unless irrational, they can be evaluated to a common =
fraction.
</p>
<ul><li>A <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_fraction" title=
=3D"Unit fraction">unit fraction</a></i> is a common fraction with a numera=
tor of 1 (e.g., <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:=
TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"t=
ion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span clas=
s=3D"den">7</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>). Unit fractions can also be expr=
essed using negative exponents, as in 2<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>, which represe=
nts 1/2, and 2<sup>=E2=88=922</sup>, which represents 1/(2<sup>2</sup>) or =
1/4.</li>
<li>A <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyadic_rational" title=3D=
"Dyadic rational">dyadic fraction</a></i> is a common fraction in which the=
 denominator is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_of_two" ti=
tle=3D"Power of two">power of two</a>, e.g. <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-in=
line-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfra=
c">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D=
"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">8</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> =3D <=
link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1=
214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=
=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2<sup>=
3</sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>.</li></ul>
<p>In Unicode, precomposed fraction characters are in the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_Forms" title=3D"Number Forms">Number Forms</=
a> block.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proper_and_improper_fractio=
ns">Proper and improper fractions</h3></div>
<p>Common fractions can be classified as either proper or improper. When th=
e numerator and the denominator are both positive, the fraction is called <=
i>proper</i> if the numerator is less than the denominator, and <i>improper=
</i> otherwise.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The concept of =
an <i>improper fraction</i> is a late development, with the terminology der=
iving from the fact that <i>fraction</i> means "piece", so a proper fractio=
n must be less than 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Smith1958_12-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-Smith1958-12=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> This was explained in the 17th century textbook <i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Ground_of_Arts" title=3D"The Ground of A=
rts">The Ground of Arts</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Williams2011_14-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note=
-Williams2011-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Record1654_15-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-Reco=
rd1654-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In general, a common fraction is said to be a <b>proper fraction</b>=
 if the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_value" title=3D"A=
bsolute value">absolute value</a> of the fraction is strictly less than one=
=E2=80=94that is, if the fraction is greater than =E2=88=921 and less than =
1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-=
17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> It is said to be an <b>improper fraction</b>, or sometimes =
<b>top-heavy fraction</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> if t=
he absolute value of the fraction is greater than or equal to 1. Examples o=
f proper fractions are 2/3, =E2=88=923/4, and 4/9, whereas examples of impr=
oper fractions are 9/4, =E2=88=924/3, and 3/3. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Fraction#Mixed_numbers">As described below</a>, any improper f=
raction can be converted to a mixed number (integer plus proper fraction), =
and vice versa.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Reciprocals_and_the_invisib=
le_denominator">Reciprocals and the invisible denominator</h3></div>
<p>The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reciprocal_(mathematics)=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Reciprocal (mathematics)">reciprocal</a></=
i> of a fraction is another fraction with the numerator and denominator exc=
hanged. The reciprocal of <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<spa=
n class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">3</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</spa=
n><span class=3D"den">7</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, for instance, is <li=
nk rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r121=
4402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D=
"num">7</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">3</span><=
/span>=E2=81=A0</span>. The product of a non-zero fraction and its reciproc=
al is 1, hence the reciprocal is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Multiplicative_inverse" title=3D"Multiplicative inverse">multiplicative =
inverse</a> of a fraction. The reciprocal of a proper fraction is improper,=
 and the reciprocal of an improper fraction not equal to 1 (that is, numera=
tor and denominator are not equal) is a proper fraction.
</p><p>When the numerator and denominator of a fraction are equal (for exam=
ple, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSty=
les:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span =
class=3D"num">7</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">7=
</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>), its value is 1, and the fraction therefore=
 is improper. Its reciprocal is identical and hence also equal to 1 and imp=
roper.
</p><p>Any integer can be written as a fraction with the number one as deno=
minator. For example, 17 can be written as <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inl=
ine-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac=
">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">17</span><span class=3D=
"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">1</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, wher=
e 1 is sometimes referred to as the <i>invisible denominator</i>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Fraction#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Therefore, every fraction and every in=
teger, except for zero, has a reciprocal. For example, the reciprocal of 17=
 is <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyl=
es:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span c=
lass=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">17=
</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ratios">Ratios</h3></div>
<p>A <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio">rat=
io</a></i> is a relationship between two or more numbers that can be someti=
mes expressed as a fraction. Typically, a number of items are grouped and c=
ompared in a ratio, specifying numerically the relationship between each gr=
oup. Ratios are expressed as "group 1 to group 2 ... to group <i>n</i>". Fo=
r example, if a car lot had 12 vehicles, of which
</p>
<ul><li>2 are white,</li>
<li>6 are red, and</li>
<li>4 are yellow,</li></ul>
<p>then the ratio of red to white to yellow cars is 6 to 2 to 4. The ratio =
of yellow cars to white cars is 4 to 2 and may be expressed as 4:2 or 2:1.
</p><p>A ratio is often converted to a fraction when it is expressed as a r=
atio to the whole. In the above example, the ratio of yellow cars to all th=
e cars on the lot is 4:12 or 1:3. We can convert these ratios to a fraction=
, and say that <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:T=
emplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"ti=
on"><span class=3D"num">4</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=
=3D"den">12</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> of the cars or <link rel=3D"mw-de=
duplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span =
class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><=
span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">3</span></span>=E2=81=A0=
</span> of the cars in the lot are yellow. Therefore, if a person randomly =
chose one car on the lot, then there is a one in three chance or <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Probability">probabili=
ty</a> that it would be yellow.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Decimal_fractions_and_perce=
ntages">Decimal fractions and percentages</h3></div>
<p>A <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_fraction" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decimal fraction">decimal fraction</a></i> is a frac=
tion whose denominator is an integer power of ten, commonly expressed using=
 decimal notation, in which the denominator is not given explicitly but is =
implied by the number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical=
_digit" title=3D"Numerical digit">digits</a> to the right of a <i>decimal s=
eparator</i>. The separator can be a period =E2=9F=A8.=E2=9F=A9, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpunct#In_mathematics_and_science" title=
=3D"Interpunct">interpunct</a> =E2=9F=A8=C2=B7=E2=9F=A9, or comma =E2=9F=A8=
,=E2=9F=A9, depending on locale. (For examples, see <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_separator#Hindu%E2%80%93Arabic_numeral_system"=
 title=3D"Decimal separator">Decimal separator</a></i>.) Thus, for 0.75 the=
 numerator is 75 and the implied denominator is 10 to the second power, nam=
ely, 100, because there are two digits to the right of the decimal separato=
r. In decimal numbers greater than 1 (such as 3.75), the <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_part" title=3D"Fractional part">fracti=
onal part</a></i> of the number is expressed by the digits to the right of =
the separator (with a value of 0.75 in this case). 3.75 can be written eith=
er as an improper fraction, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<spa=
n class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">375</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</s=
pan><span class=3D"den">100</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, or as a mixed nu=
mber, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSt=
yles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A03<span class=3D"sr-only">+=
</span><span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">75</span><span class=3D"sr-=
only">/</span><span class=3D"den">100</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>.
</p><p>Decimal fractions can also be expressed using <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation" title=3D"Scientific notation">scien=
tific notation</a> with negative exponents, such as <span class=3D"nowrap">=
<span data-sort-value=3D"6993602299999999999=E2=99=A0"></span>6.023<span st=
yle=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=
=927</sup></span>, a convenient alternative to the unwieldy 0.0000006023. T=
he <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6993100000000000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>10<sup>=E2=88=927</sup></span> represents a denominator of <=
span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7007100000000000000=E2=99=A0=
"></span>10<sup>7</sup></span>. Dividing by <span class=3D"nowrap"><span da=
ta-sort-value=3D"7007100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>7</sup></span>=
 moves the decimal point seven places to the left.
</p><p>A decimal fraction with infinitely many digits to the right of the d=
ecimal separator represents an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inf=
inite_series" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinite series">infinite seri=
es</a>. For example, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-=
data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span=
 class=3D"den">3</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> =3D 0.333... represents the =
infinite series 3/10 + 3/100 + 3/1000 + ....
</p><p>Another kind of fraction is the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Percentage" title=3D"Percentage">percentage</a></i> (from <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Latin language">Latin</a>: <i lang=3D"la">per centum</i>, meaning "pe=
r hundred", represented by the symbol&nbsp;%), in which the implied denomin=
ator is always 100. Thus, 51% means <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-sty=
le" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span =
class=3D"num">51</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">100</span></span>. Perc=
entages greater than 100 or less than zero are treated in the same way, e.g=
. 311% means <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Tem=
plateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">311</span=
>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">100</span></span> and =E2=88=9227% means <lin=
k rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154=
941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">=E2=88=9227</span>=E2=81=
=84<span class=3D"den">100</span></span>.
</p><p>The related concept of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ermille" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Permille">permille</a></i>, or <i>p=
arts per thousand</i> (ppt), means a denominator of 1000, and this <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parts-per_notation" title=3D"Parts-per no=
tation"><i>parts-per</i> notation</a> is commonly used with larger denomina=
tors, such as <i>million</i> and <i>billion</i>, e.g. <i>75 parts per milli=
on</i> (<i>ppm</i>) means that the proportion is <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicat=
ed-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D=
"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">75</span><span cl=
ass=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den"><span class=3D"nowrap"><span da=
ta-sort-value=3D"7006100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1<span style=3D"margi=
n-left:.25em;">000</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000</span></spa=
n></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>.
</p><p>The choice between fraction and decimal notation is often a matter o=
f taste and context. Fractions are used most often when the denominator is =
relatively small. By <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mental_calcul=
ation" title=3D"Mental calculation">mental calculation</a>, it is easier to=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiply" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Multiply">multiply</a> 16 by <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-st=
yle" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span=
 class=3D"num">3</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">16</span></span> than t=
o do the same calculation using the fraction's decimal equivalent (0.1875).=
 And it is more <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy_and_preci=
sion" title=3D"Accuracy and precision">precise</a> (exact, in fact) to mult=
iply 15 by <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templ=
ateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=
=81=84<span class=3D"den">3</span></span>, for example, than it is to multi=
ply 15 by any decimal approximation of one third. Monetary values are commo=
nly expressed as decimal fractions with denominator 100, i.e., with two dig=
its after the decimal separator, for example <i>$3.75</i>. However, as note=
d above, in pre-decimal British currency, shillings and pence were often gi=
ven the form (but not the meaning) of a fraction, as, for example, "3/6", c=
ommonly read <i>three and six</i>, means <i>three&nbsp;shillings and sixpen=
ce</i> and has no relationship to the fraction <i>three sixths</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mixed_numbers">Mixed number=
s</h3></div>
<p>A <i>mixed number</i> (also called a <i>mixed fraction</i> or <i>mixed n=
umeral</i>) is the sum of a non-zero integer and a proper fraction, convent=
ionally written by juxtaposition (or <i>concatenation</i>) of the two parts=
