<p>The smallest possible denominator is given by the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_common_multiple" title=3D"Least common multiple">l=
east common multiple</a> of the single denominators, which results from div=
iding the rote multiple by all common factors of the single denominators. T=
his is called the least common denominator.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Subtraction">Subtraction</h=
3></div>
<p>The process for subtracting fractions is, in essence, the same as that o=
f adding them: find a common denominator, and change each fraction to an eq=
uivalent fraction with the chosen common denominator. The resulting fractio=
n will have that denominator, and its numerator will be the result of subtr=
acting the numerators of the original fractions. For instance,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\tfrac {2}{3}}-{\tfrac {1}{2}}=3D{\tfrac {4}{6}}-{\tfrac {3}{6}}=3D{\tfr=
ac {1}{6}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
            <mfrac>
              <mn>2</mn>
              <mn>3</mn>
            </mfrac>
          </mstyle>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
