23=3D{\tfrac {123}{100}}.}"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Converting_repeating_digits=
_in_decimal_notation_to_fractions">Converting repeating digits in decimal n=
otation to fractions</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_repre=
sentation#Conversion_to_fraction" title=3D"Decimal representation">Decimal =
representation =C2=A7&nbsp;Conversion to fraction</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repeating_decimal" title=
=3D"Repeating decimal">Repeating decimal</a></div>
<p>Decimal numbers, while arguably more useful to work with when performing=
 calculations, sometimes lack the precision that common fractions have. Som=
etimes an infinite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repeating_decim=
al" title=3D"Repeating decimal">repeating decimal</a> is required to reach =
the same precision. Thus, it is often useful to convert repeating digits in=
to fractions.
</p><p>A conventional way to indicate a repeating decimal is to place a bar=
 (known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinculum_(symbol)" ti=
tle=3D"Vinculum (symbol)">vinculum</a>) over the digits that repeat, for ex=
ample 0.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">789</span> =3D 0.78978978=
9.... For repeating patterns that begin immediately after the decimal point=
, the result of the conversion is the fraction with the pattern as a numera=
tor, and the same number of nines as a denominator. For example:
</p>
<dl><dd>0.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">5</span> =3D 5/9</dd>
<dd>0.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">62</span> =3D 62/99</dd>
<dd>0.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">264</span> =3D 264/999</dd>
<dd>0.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">6291</span> =3D 6291/9999</=
dd></dl>
<p>If <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leading_zero" title=3D"Leadi=
ng zero">leading zeros</a> precede the pattern, the nines are suffixed by t=
he same number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trailing_zero" t=
itle=3D"Trailing zero">trailing zeros</a>:
</p>
<dl><dd>0.0<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">5</span> =3D 5/90</dd>
<dd>0.000<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">392</span> =3D 392/99900=
0</dd>
<dd>0.00<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">12</span> =3D 12/9900</dd=
></dl>
<p>If a non-repeating set of digits precede the pattern (such as 0.1523<spa=
n style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">987</span>), one may write the number=
 as the sum of the non-repeating and repeating parts, respectively:
</p>
<dl><dd>0.1523 + 0.0000<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">987</span>=
</dd></dl>
<p>Then, convert both parts to fractions, and add them using the methods de=
scribed above:
</p>
<dl><dd>1523 / 10000 + 987 / 9990000 =3D 1522464 / 9990000</dd></dl>
<p>Alternatively, algebra can be used, such as below:
</p>
<ol><li>Let <i>x</i> =3D the repeating decimal:
<dl><dd><i>x</i> =3D 0.1523<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">987</s=
pan></dd></dl></li>
<li>Multiply both sides by the power of 10 just great enough (in this case =
10<sup>4</sup>) to move the decimal point just before the repeating part of=
 the decimal number:
<dl><dd>10,000<i>x</i> =3D 1,523.<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">=
987</span></dd></dl></li>
<li>Multiply both sides by the power of 10 (in this case 10<sup>3</sup>) th=
at is the same as the number of places that repeat:
<dl><dd>10,000,000<i>x</i> =3D 1,523,987.<span style=3D"text-decoration:ove=
rline;">987</span></dd></dl></li>
<li>Subtract the two equations from each other (if <span class=3D"nowrap"><=
i>a</i> =3D <i>b</i></span> and <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>c</i> =3D <i>d</i=
></span>, then <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i> =E2=88=92 <i>c</i> =3D <i>b<=
/i> =E2=88=92 <i>d</i></span>):
<dl><dd>10,000,000<i>x</i> =E2=88=92 10,000<i>x</i> =3D 1,523,987.<span sty=
le=3D"text-decoration:overline;">987</span> =E2=88=92 1,523.<span style=3D"=
text-decoration:overline;">987</span></dd></dl></li>
<li>Continue the subtraction operation to clear the repeating decimal:
<dl><dd>9,990,000<i>x</i> =3D 1,523,987 =E2=88=92 1,523</dd>
<dd><span style=3D"visibility:hidden">9,990,000<i>x</i></span> =3D 1,522,46=
4</dd></dl></li>
<li>Divide both sides by 9,990,000 to represent <i>x</i> as a fraction
<dl><dd><i>x</i> =3D <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-=
data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1522464</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span=
><span class=3D"den">9990000</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></dd></dl></li></=
ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Fractions_in_abstract_mathe=
matics">Fractions in abstract mathematics</h2></div>
