<p>Even if this process results in the numerator being irrational, like in =
the examples above, the process may still facilitate subsequent manipulatio=
ns by reducing the number of irrationals one has to work with in the denomi=
nator.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Typographical_variations">T=
ypographical variations</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slash_(punctuation)#Enco=
ding" title=3D"Slash (punctuation)">Slash =C2=A7 Encoding</a></div>
<p>In computer displays and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typogr=
aphy" title=3D"Typography">typography</a>, simple fractions are sometimes p=
rinted as a single character, e.g. =C2=BD (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/One_half" title=3D"One half">one half</a>). See the article on <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_Forms" title=3D"Number Forms">=
Number Forms</a> for information on doing this in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Unicode" title=3D"Unicode">Unicode</a>.
</p><p>Scientific publishing distinguishes four ways to set fractions, toge=
ther with guidelines on use:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-galen_31-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-galen-31">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Special fractions: fractions that are presented as a single charact=
er with a slanted bar, with roughly the same height and width as other char=
acters in the text. Generally used for simple fractions, such as: =C2=BD, =
=E2=85=93, =E2=85=94, =C2=BC, and =C2=BE. Since the numerals are smaller, l=
egibility can be an issue, especially for small-sized fonts. These are not =
used in modern mathematical notation but in other contexts.</li>
<li>Case fractions: similar to special fractions, these are rendered as a s=
ingle typographical character, but with a horizontal bar, thus making them =
<i>upright</i>. An example would be <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-sty=
le" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=
=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-on=
ly">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, but render=
ed with the same height as other characters. Some sources include all rende=
ring of fractions as <i>case fractions</i> if they take only one typographi=
cal space, regardless of the direction of the bar.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_n=
ote-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Shilling, or solidus, fractions: 1/2, so called because this notation w=
as used for pre-decimal British currency (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/%C2%A3sd" title=3D"=C2=A3sd">=C2=A3sd</a>), as in "2/6" for a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half_crown_(British_coin)" title=3D"Hal=
f crown (British coin)">half crown</a>, meaning two shillings and six pence=
. While the notation <i>two shillings and six pence</i> did not represent a=
 fraction, the slash is now used in fractions, especially for fractions inl=
ine with prose (rather than displayed), to avoid uneven lines. It is also u=
sed for fractions within fractions (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Fraction#Complex_fractions">complex fractions</a>) or within exponents to=
 increase legibility. Fractions written this way, also known as <i>piece fr=
actions</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> are written all on=
 one typographical line but take three or more typographical spaces.</li>
<li>Built-up fractions: <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-in=
line"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"=
display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle {\frac {1}{2}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {1}{2}=
}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a11cfb2fdb143693b1daf78fcb5c11a023cb1c55" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:1.999ex; height:5.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\f=
rac {1}{2}}}"></span>. This notation uses two or more lines of ordinary tex=
t and results in a variation in spacing between lines when included within =
other text. While large and legible, these can be disruptive, particularly =
for simple fractions or within complex fractions.</li></ul>
