<p>The earliest fractions were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mul=
tiplicative_inverse" title=3D"Multiplicative inverse">reciprocals</a> of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers<=
/a>: ancient symbols representing one part of two, one part of three, one p=
art of four, and so on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-eves_34-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-eves-34"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> The Egyptians used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_f=
raction" title=3D"Egyptian fraction">Egyptian fractions</a> <span title=3D"=
circa">c.</span><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891000</span>&nb=
sp;BC. About 4000 years ago, Egyptians divided with fractions using slightl=
y different methods. They used least common multiples with <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_fraction" title=3D"Unit fraction">unit fracti=
ons</a>. Their methods gave the same answer as modern methods.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fra=
ction#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Egyptians also had a different notation=
 for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyadic_fraction" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Dyadic fraction">dyadic fractions</a>, used for certain =
systems of weights and measures.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-36"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title=
=3D"Ancient Greece">Greeks</a> used unit fractions and (later) <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_continued_fraction" title=3D"Simple con=
tinued fraction">simple continued fractions</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pythagoreans" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pythagoreans">F=
ollowers</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece=
" title=3D"Ancient Greece">Greek</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Greek_philosophy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Greek philosophy">philo=
sopher</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title=3D"Py=
thagoras">Pythagoras</a> (<span title=3D"circa">c.</span><span style=3D"whi=
te-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89530</span>&nbsp;BC) discovered that the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root_of_two" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Square root of two">square root of two</a> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Irrat=
ional numbers">cannot be expressed as a fraction of integers</a>. (This is =
commonly though probably erroneously ascribed to <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Hippasus" title=3D"Hippasus">Hippasus</a> of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metapontum" title=3D"Metapontum">Metapontum</a>, =
who is said to have been executed for revealing this fact.) In <span class=
=3D"nowrap">150 BC</span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Jain">Jain</a> mathematicians in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_India" title=3D"History of India">In=
dia</a> wrote the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sthananga_Sut=
ra" title=3D"Sthananga Sutra">Sthananga Sutra</a></i>, which contains work =
on the theory of numbers, arithmetical operations, and operations with frac=
tions.
</p><p>A modern expression of fractions known as <b>bhinnarasi</b> seems to=
 have originated in India in the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Aryabhatta" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Aryabhatta">Aryabhatta</a=
> (<span title=3D"circa">c.</span><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=
=80=89AD 500</span>),<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" s=
tyle=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
ikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=
=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2016)">citat=
ion needed</span></a></i>]</sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
rahmagupta" title=3D"Brahmagupta">Brahmagupta</a> (<span title=3D"circa">c.=
</span><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89628</span>), and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bh%C4%81skara_II" title=3D"Bh=C4=81skara=
 II">Bhaskara</a> (<span title=3D"circa">c.</span><span style=3D"white-spac=
e:nowrap;">=E2=80=891150</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-jeff_37-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-jeff-3=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> Their works form fractions by placing the numerators (<a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit_language" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Sanskrit language">Sanskrit</a>: <i lang=3D"sa">amsa</i>) over th=
e denominators (<span title=3D"Sanskrit-language text"><i lang=3D"sa">cheda=
</i></span>), but without a bar between them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-jeff_37-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite=
_note-jeff-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sans=
krit_literature" title=3D"Sanskrit literature">Sanskrit literature</a>, fra=
ctions were always expressed as an addition to or subtraction from an integ=
er.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-spac=
e:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_=
needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs=
 references to reliable sources. (February 2016)">citation needed</span></a=
></i>]</sup> The integer was written on one line and the fraction in its tw=
o parts on the next line. If the fraction was marked by a small circle <spa=
n class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8=E0=A5=A6=E2=9F=A9</span> or cross <span class=
=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8+=E2=9F=A9</span>, it is subtracted from the integer; =
if no such sign appears, it is understood to be added. For example, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhaskara_I" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Bhaskara I">Bhaskara I</a> writes:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-filliozat-p152_38=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#c=
ite_note-filliozat-p152-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd>=E0=A5=AC  =E0=A5=A7  =E0=A5=A8</dd>
<dd>=E0=A5=A7  =E0=A5=A7  =E0=A5=A7<sub>=E0=A5=A6</sub></dd>
<dd>=E0=A5=AA  =E0=A5=AB  =E0=A5=AF</dd></dl>
<p>which is the equivalent of
</p>
<dl><dd>6  1  2</dd>
<dd>1  1  =E2=88=921</dd>
<dd>4   5  9</dd></dl>
<p>and would be written in modern notation as 6<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated=
-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"s=
frac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=
=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, 1=
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=
=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">5</spa=
n></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, and 2&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;<link rel=3D"mw-dedupl=
icated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span clas=
s=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span=
 class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">9</span></span>=E2=81=A0</sp=
an> (i.e., 1<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Temp=
lateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"=
><span class=3D"num">8</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D=
"den">9</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>).
</p><p>The horizontal fraction bar is first attested in the work of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Hass%C4%81r" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Al-Hass=C4=81r">Al-Hass=C4=81r</a> (<abbr title=3D"floruit ('flourish=
ed'&nbsp;=E2=80=93 known to have been active at a particular time or during=
 a particular period)">fl.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=
=891200</span>),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-jeff_37-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction#cite_note-jeff-37"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_in_medieval_Islam" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematics in medieval Islam">Muslim mathem=
atician</a> from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fes" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Fes">Fez</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
orocco" title=3D"Morocco">Morocco</a>, who specialized in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamic_inheritance_jurisprudence" title=3D"Islamic=
 inheritance jurisprudence">Islamic inheritance jurisprudence</a>. In his d=
iscussion he writes: "for example, if you are told to write three-fifths an=
d a third of a fifth, write thus, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inlin=
e mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\frac {3\quad 1}{5\quad=
